{"title_page": "The Dumbfounded King", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = El rey pasmado\n| image          = EL REY PASMADO.jpg\n| image size     =\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Imanol Uribe]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Joan Potau]]<br/>[[Gonzalo Torrente Ballester]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Gabino Diego]]<br/>[[Juan Diego (actor)|Juan Diego]]<br/>[[Mar\u00eda Barranco]]<br/>[[Javier Garruchaga]]\n| music          = [[Jos\u00e9 Nieto (composer)|Jos\u00e9 Nieto]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = [[Teresa Font]]\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1 November 1991\n| runtime        = 106 minutes\n| country        = [[Spain]]/[[France]]/[[Portugal]]\n| language       = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded by    = \n| followed by    = \n}}\n'''''El rey pasmado''''' ([[English language|English]]: ''The Dumbfounded King'') is a 1991 [[France|French]]-[[Portugal|Portuguese]]-[[Spain|Spanish]] comedy-historical [[film]] directed by [[Imanol Uribe]] and written by [[Joan Potau]] and [[Gonzalo Torrente Ballester]]. The screenplay was based on Torrente's novel ''[[Cr\u00f3nica del rey pasmado]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nStory set in 17th century Spanish court, where King [[Philip IV of Spain|Philip IV]] ([[Gabino Diego]]), on a getaway with Count of Pe\u00f1a Andrada, is stunned to see the naked body of Marfisa, a prostitute of the town (in a pose reminiscent of the [[Rokeby Venus]]). After this discovery, the king decides to see the naked body of his wife, Queen [[Elisabeth of France (1602\u20131644)|Elisabeth of France]] ([[Anne Roussel]])\n\nDue to this the [[Grand Inquisitor]] is obliged to convene a meeting of theologians to discuss the matter. Both sides of the debate are represented by the figure of the friar Villaescusa (Juan Diego), which ensures that the claim of the king is a serious sin that can bring punishment on the whole country and the Father Almeida, a [[Jesuit]] missionary who replies that the luck of the governed depends on the ability of its rulers rather than their morality and that the desire of the king is a private matter. Although the Queen is willing to accommodate to the wishes of the king, Villaescusa and his minions do enough to frustrate his desires. Finally, with the help of the Jesuit and the Count of la Pe\u00f1a Andrada, the King gets to meet with the queen alone in the [[Convent of San Pl\u00e1cido (Madrid)|monastery of San Pl\u00e1cido]] and achieves his goal.\n\nMeanwhile, the [[Gaspar de Guzm\u00e1n, Count-Duke of Olivares|Count-Duke of Olivares]] ([[Javier Gurruchag]]a) fears that he could being punished by God because he fails to have children with his wife, so he gets advice from Villaescusa, who informs him that the pleasure he and his wife obtain when performing the sexual act is to be blamed for the infertility. The \"divinely inspired\" solution proposed by Villaescusa is that the Earl and his wife copulate in the choir of the church of San Pl\u00e1cido (where by coincidence are also very nearly the kings) in front of the choir nuns. At the end of this sexual encounter the Count-Duke of Olivares receives two letters which informs him of the successful arrival of the Indian fleet to [[Cadiz]] and the victory of Spanish troops in Flanders. Villaescusa says that the happy ending is due to the sacrifices they all have passed, but the Count Duke replies that by the date of the letters it could be seen that the fleet had arrived in Cadiz two days ago \"just the day King went whores\". The Count-Duke sends Villaescusa to Rome with a sealed letter asking to not let him go until he has changed his attitude.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Gabino Diego]] as The King\n*[[Laura del Sol]] as Marfisa\n*[[Joaquim de Almeida]] as Father Almeida\n*[[Mar\u00eda Barranco]] as Lucrecia\n*[[Juan Diego (actor)|Juan Diego]] as Father Villaescusa\n*[[Fernando Fern\u00e1n G\u00f3mez]] as Grand Inquisitor\n*[[Javier Gurruchaga]] as Valido\n*[[Anne Roussel]] as The Queen\n*[[Carme El\u00edas]] as Abesse\n\n==Production==\nMost of the film was shot in the [[Palacio del Marqu\u00e9s de Santa Cruz (Viso)|Renaissance palace of the Marquis of Santa Cruz]] in [[Viso del Marqu\u00e9s]] (Ciudad Real) and the [[Monastery of Ucl\u00e9s]] (Cuenca).\n\n==Reception==\nSpanish critic [[Carlos Aguilar (writer)|Carlos Aguilar]] in his ''Gu\u00eda del cine espa\u00f1ol'' says that the film has some flaws, such as the different treatment of historical characters, but these are outweighed by good realization and a good cast.<ref>{{cite book |last= Aguilar |first= Carlos |enlaceautor= |title= Gu\u00eda del cine espa\u00f1ol |url= |accessdate= |language= |others= |edici\u00f3n= |year= 2007 |editor= |publisher= C\u00e1tedra|location= |isbn=978-84-376-2419-8 |chapter= |pages= 885 |work= }}</ref> Critics also noted the close resemblance of Gabino Diego and Gurruchaga with Philip IV and the Count-Duke of Olivares respectively.<ref>[http://www.cinehistoria.com/rey_pasmado.pdf El rey pasmado] en cineshistoria.com</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===Won===\n*'''[[6th Goya Awards|Goya Awards]]'''\n**Best Actor in a Supporting Role (Juan Diego)\n**Best Costume Design (Javier Arti\u00f1ano)\n**Best Makeup and Hairstyles (Romana Gonz\u00e1lez and Josefa Morales)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] (Jos\u00e9 Nieto)\n**Best Production Design (F\u00e9lix Murcia)\n**Best Production Supervision (Andr\u00e9s Santana)\n**Best Screenplay &ndash; Adapted (Joan Potau and Gonzalo Torrente Malvido)\n**Best Sound (Ricard Casals and Gilles Ortion)\n\n===Nominated===\n*'''[[6th Goya Awards|Goya Awards]]'''\n**Best Actor in a Leading Role (Gabino Diego)\n**Best Actor in a Supporting Role (Javier Gurruchaga)\n**Best Actress in a Supporting Role (Mar\u00eda Barranco)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] (Hans Burman)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (Imanol Uribe)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0102788|title=The Dumbfounded King (El rey pasmado)}}\n* {{AllMovie movie|211251|The Dumbfounded King (El rey pasmado)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumbfounded King}}\n[[Category:1991 films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1620s]]\n[[Category:Spanish comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Madrid]]\n[[Category:Spanish films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Portuguese films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = El rey pasmado\n| image          = EL REY PASMADO.jpg\n| image size     =\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Imanol Uribe]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Joan Potau]]<br/>[[Gonzalo Torrente Ballester]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Gabino Diego]]<br/>[[Juan Diego (actor)|Juan Diego]]<br/>[[Mar\u00eda Barranco]]<br/>[[Javier Garruchaga]]\n| music          = [[Jos\u00e9 Nieto (composer)|Jos\u00e9 Nieto]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = [[Teresa Font]]\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1 November 1991\n| runtime        = 106 minutes\n| country        = [[Spain]]/[[France]]/[[Portugal]]\n| language       = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded by    = \n| followed by    = \n}}\n'''''El rey pasmado''''' ([[English language|English]]: ''The Dumbfounded King'') is a 1991 [[France|French]]-[[Portugal|Portuguese]]-[[Spain|Spanish]] comedy-historical [[film]] directed by [[Imanol Uribe]] and written by [[Joan Potau]] and [[Gonzalo Torrente Ballester]]. The screenplay was based on Torrente's novel ''[[Cr\u00f3nica del rey pasmado]]''.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Gabino Diego]] as The King\n*[[Laura del Sol]] as Marfisa\n*[[Joaquim de Almeida]] as Father Almeida\n*[[Mar\u00eda Barranco]] as Lucrecia\n*[[Juan Diego (actor)|Juan Diego]] as Father Villaescusa\n*[[Fernando Fern\u00e1n G\u00f3mez]] as Grand Inquisitor\n*[[Javier Gurruchaga]] as Valido\n*[[Anne Roussel]] as The Queen\n*[[Carme El\u00edas]] as Abesse\n\n==Plot==\nStory set in 17th century Spanish court, where King [[Philip IV of Spain|Philip IV]] ([[Gabino Diego]]), on a getaway with Count of Pe\u00f1a Andrada, is stunned to see the naked body of Marfisa, a prostitute of the town (in a pose reminiscent of the [[Rokeby Venus]]). After this discovery, the king decides to see the naked body of his wife, Queen [[Elisabeth of France (1602\u20131644)|Elisabeth of France]] ([[Anne Roussel]])\n\nDue to this the [[Grand Inquisitor]] is obliged to convene a meeting of theologians to discuss the matter. Both sides of the debate are represented by the figure of the friar Villaescusa (Juan Diego), which ensures that the claim of the king is a serious sin that can bring punishment on the whole country and the Father Almeida, a [[Jesuit]] missionary who replies that the luck of the governed depends on the ability of its rulers rather than their morality and that the desire of the king is a private matter. Although the Queen is willing to accommodate to the wishes of the king, Villaescusa and his minions do enough to frustrate his desires. Finally, with the help of the Jesuit and the Count of la Pe\u00f1a Andrada, the King gets to meet with the queen alone in the [[Convent of San Pl\u00e1cido (Madrid)|monastery of San Pl\u00e1cido]] and achieves his goal.\n\nMeanwhile, the [[Gaspar de Guzm\u00e1n, Count-Duke of Olivares|Count-Duke of Olivares]] ([[Javier Gurruchag]]a) fears that he could being punished by God because he fails to have children with his wife, so he gets advice from Villaescusa, who informs him that the pleasure he and his wife obtain when performing the sexual act is to be blamed for the infertility. The \"divinely inspired\" solution proposed by Villaescusa is that the Earl and his wife copulate in the choir of the church of San Pl\u00e1cido (where by coincidence are also very nearly the kings) in front of the choir nuns. At the end of this sexual encounter the Count-Duke of Olivares receives two letters which informs him of the successful arrival of the Indian fleet to [[Cadiz]] and the victory of Spanish troops in Flanders. Villaescusa says that the happy ending is due to the sacrifices they all have passed, but the Count Duke replies that by the date of the letters it could be seen that the fleet had arrived in Cadiz two days ago \"just the day King went whores\". The Count-Duke sends Villaescusa to Rome with a sealed letter asking to not let him go until he has changed his attitude.\n\n==Critic==\nSpanish critic [[Carlos Aguilar (writer)|Carlos Aguilar]] in his ''Gu\u00eda del cine espa\u00f1ol'' says that the film has some flaws, such as the different treatment of historical characters, but these are outweighed by good realization and a good cast.<ref>{{cite book |last= Aguilar |first= Carlos |enlaceautor= |title= Gu\u00eda del cine espa\u00f1ol |url= |accessdate= |language= |others= |edici\u00f3n= |year= 2007 |editor= |publisher= C\u00e1tedra|location= |isbn=978-84-376-2419-8 |chapter= |pages= 885 |work= }}</ref> Critics also noted the close resemblance of Gabino Diego and Gurruchaga with Philip IV and the Count-Duke of Olivares respectively.<ref>[http://www.cinehistoria.com/rey_pasmado.pdf El rey pasmado] en cineshistoria.com</ref>\n\nMost of the film was shot in the [[Palacio del Marqu\u00e9s de Santa Cruz (Viso)|Renaissance palace of the Marquis of Santa Cruz]] in [[Viso del Marqu\u00e9s]] (Ciudad Real) and the [[Monastery of Ucl\u00e9s]] (Cuenca).\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===Won===\n*'''[[6th Goya Awards|Goya Awards]]'''\n**Best Actor in a Supporting Role (Juan Diego)\n**Best Costume Design (Javier Arti\u00f1ano)\n**Best Makeup and Hairstyles (Romana Gonz\u00e1lez and Josefa Morales)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] (Jos\u00e9 Nieto)\n**Best Production Design (F\u00e9lix Murcia)\n**Best Production Supervision (Andr\u00e9s Santana)\n**Best Screenplay &ndash; Adapted (Joan Potau and Gonzalo Torrente Malvido)\n**Best Sound (Ricard Casals and Gilles Ortion)\n\n===Nominated===\n*'''[[6th Goya Awards|Goya Awards]]'''\n**Best Actor in a Leading Role (Gabino Diego)\n**Best Actor in a Supporting Role (Javier Gurruchaga)\n**Best Actress in a Supporting Role (Mar\u00eda Barranco)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] (Hans Burman)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (Imanol Uribe)\n**[[Goya Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0102788|title=The Dumbfounded King (El rey pasmado)}}\n* {{Amg movie|211251|The Dumbfounded King (El rey pasmado)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumbfounded King}}\n[[Category:1991 films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1620s]]\n[[Category:Spanish comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Madrid]]\n[[Category:Spanish films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Portuguese films]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "layout, headings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dumbfounded_King"}
