702#released DistroWatch Weekly, Issue 770, 2 July 2018]</ref>\n| {{dts|2018-06-26}}<ref name=\"version3.8\" />\n|\n|-\n| {{Version | o | 3.9}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_3.9/index.en.html|title=Tails - Tails 3.9 is out|website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref><ref name=\"tails_calendar\">{{cite web |url=https://tails.boum.org/contribute/calendar/ |title=Tails - Calendar |date=2018-07-17 |accessdate=2018-07-17 }}</ref>\n| {{dts|2018-09-05}}<ref name=\"tails_calendar\" />\n|\n*Firefox 60.2, major release; will include VeraCrypt support and major Additional Software Packages improvements.<ref name=\"tails_calendar\" />\n|-\n|{{Version | o | 3.9.1}}<ref name=\"version3.9\">{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_3.9.1/index.en.html|title=Tails - Release notes|website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n|October 3, 2018<ref name=\"version3.9\" />\n|\n* Update ''Tor Browser'' to 8.0.2.  This fixes 2 critical security vulnerabilities in JavaScript in ''Firefox''.\n* Update ''Thunderbird'' to fix these same vulnerabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_3.9.1/index.en.html|title=Tails - Tails 3.9.1 is out|website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{Version | o | 3.10.1}}<ref name=\"version3.10\">{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_3.10.1/index.en.html|title=Tails 3.10.1 is out |website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n|October 23, 2018\n|\n* Hide the '''PIM''' option when unlocking ''VeraCrypt'' volumes because ''PIM'' won't be supported until Tails 4.0. (#16031)\n* Rename the buttons in the confirmation dialog of ''Tails Installer'' to '''Install''' (or '''Upgrade''') and '''Cancel''' to be less confusing. (#11501)\n* Update ''Linux'' to 4.8.\n* Update ''Tor Browser'' to 8.0.3.\n* Update ''Thunderbird'' to 60.2.1.\n|-\n|{{Version | o | 4.0}}<ref name=\"version4.0\">{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_4.0/index.en.html|title=Tails 4.0 is out |website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n|October 22, 2019<ref name=\"version4.0\" />\n|\n* Replace KeePassX with KeePassXC\n* Update ''Linux'' to 5.3.2\n* Update ''OnionShare'' to 1.3.2\n* Update ''Tor Browser'' to 9.0<ref name=\"version4.0\" />\n|-\n|{{Version | o | 4.1}}<ref name=\"version4.1\">{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_4.1/index.en.html|title=Tails 4.1 is out |website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n|December 3, 2019<ref name=\"version4.1\" />\n|\n|-\n|{{Version | o | 4.1.1}}<ref name=\"version4.1.1\">{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_4.1.1/index.en.html|title=Tails 4.1.1 is out |website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n|December 17, 2019<ref name=\"version4.1.1\" />\n|\n|-\n|{{Version | o | 4.2}}<ref name=\"version4.2\">{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_4.2/index.en.html|title=Tails 4.2 is out |website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2012-01-07}}</ref>\n|January 7, 2020<ref name=\"version4.2\" />\n|\n* Update Tor Browser to 9.0.3\n* Update Thunderbird to 68.3.0\n* Update Linux to 5.3.15<ref name=\"version4.2\" />\n|-\n|{{Version | c | 4.3}}<ref name=\"version4.3\">{{Cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/contribute/calendar/|title=Tails - Calendar |website=tails.boum.org|access-date=2012-01-07}}</ref>\n|February 11, 2020<ref name=\"version4.3\" />\n|\n* Updated {{em|Tor Browser}} to 9.0.5\n* Updated {{em|Thunderbird}} to 68.4.1\n* Updated {{em|Linux Kernel}} to 5.4.13\n* Updated {{em|Tor}} to 0.4.2.6\n* Updated {{em|Virtualbox Guest Additions}} to 6.1.2\n|-\n! Version\n! Release date\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|}\n\n==In mainstream media==\nOn 3 July 2014, German public television channel ''[[Das Erste]]'' reported that the [[NSA]]'s [[XKeyscore]] surveillance system contains definitions that match persons who search for Tails using a search engine or visit the Tails website. A [[Comment (computer programming)|comment]] in XKeyscore's source code calls Tails \"a [[Communications security|comsec]] mechanism advocated by [[Extremism|extremists]] on extremist forums\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daserste.ndr.de/panorama/aktuell/NSA-targets-the-privacy-conscious,nsa230.html|author=[[Jacob Appelbaum]], A. Gibson, J. Goetz, V. Kabisch, L. Kampf, L. Ryge|title=NSA targets the privacy-conscious|publisher=DasErste.de |date=3 Jul 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2014/07/nsa_targets_pri.html|title=NSA Targets Privacy Conscious for Surveillance|author=[[Bruce Schneier]]|work=Schneier on Security|date=3 Jul 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 December 2014, ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' published slides from an internal [[NSA]] presentation dating to June 2012 in which the NSA deemed Tails on its own as a \"major threat\" to its mission, and when used in conjunction with other privacy tools such as [[Off-the-Record Messaging|OTR]], Cspace, [[RedPhone]], and [[TrueCrypt]] was ranked as \"catastrophic,\" leading to a \"near-total loss/lack of insight to target communications, presence...\"<ref name=\"spiegel1\" /><ref name=\"spiegel2\" />\n\n== Tails partners ==\nOrganizations, companies and individuals that provide financial support to Tails through grants or donations are recognized as \"partners\",<ref>{{cite web |title=Tails: Partners |url=https://tails.boum.org/partners/become/ |accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> and have included:\n\n* [https://handshakefoundation.org Handshake Foundation]\n* [https://www.opentech.fund/ Open Technology Fund]\n* [[DuckDuckGo]]\n* [https://uk.lush.com/article/digital-fund-one-year-later Lush]\n* [[I2P]]\n* [[The Tor Project, Inc|Tor]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Crypto-anarchism]]\n* [[Dark web]]\n* [[Deep web]]\n* [[Freedom of information]]\n* [[GlobaLeaks]]\n* [[GNU Privacy Guard]]\n* [[I2P]]\n* [[Internet censorship]]\n* [[Internet privacy]]\n* [[Off-the-Record Messaging]]\n* [[Proxy server]]\n* [[Security-focused operating system]]s\n* [[Tor (anonymity network)]]\n* [[Tor2web]]\n* [[Whonix]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"spiegel2\">{{cite magazine|title=Presentation from the SIGDEV Conference 2012 explaining which encryption protocols and techniques can be attacked and which not|url=http://www.spiegel.de/media/media-35535.pdf|magazine=Der Spiegel|accessdate=23 Jan 2015|format=PDF|date=28 Dec 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"spiegel1\">{{cite news|author=SPIEGEL Staff|title=Prying Eyes: Inside the NSA's War on Internet Security|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/inside-the-nsa-s-war-on-internet-security-a-1010361.html|newspaper=Der Spiegel|accessdate=23 Jan 2015|date=28 Dec 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"h\">{{citation |url=http://www.h-online.com/open/news/item/Tails-0-11-incognito-live-system-released-1563498.html |title=Tails 0.11 incognito live system released |first= |last= |work=[[The H]] |date=30 Apr 2012 |accessdate=12 Aug 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"lj\">{{citation |url=http://www.linuxjournal.com/content/tails-projects-amnesic-incognito-live-system-tails |title=The Tails Project's The Amnesic Incognito Live System (Tails) |first=James |last=Gray |work=[[Linux Journal]] |date=16 Sep 2011 |accessdate=12 Aug 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"lwn\">{{citation |url=https://lwn.net/Articles/440279/ |title=The Amnesic Incognito Live System: A live CD for anonymity |first=Koen |last=Vervloesem |work=[[LWN.net]] |date=27 Apr 2011 |accessdate=12 Aug 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"tc\">{{citation |language=German |url=http://www.tecchannel.de/sicherheit/news/2038771/tails_0101_the_amnesic_incognito_live_system/ |title=Anonym im Netz |trans-title=Anonymous on the Net |first= |last= |work=[[TecChannel]] |date=6 Feb 2012 |accessdate=12 Aug 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|The Amnesic Incognito Live System}}\n* {{Official website|https://tails.boum.org}}\n* [https://www.torproject.org/projects/projects.html.en Tails] at Tor project website\n* [https://tails.boum.org/support/known_issues/index.en.html Tails - Known issues]\n* [https://deeponion.org/community/threads/tails-deeponion-partnership-soon-to-start.39854/ Tails] at DeepOnion Website\n* {{distrowatch|tails|NAME=Tails}}\n\n{{Tor project}}\n{{Linux distributions}}\n{{Portal bar|Anarchism|Free and open-source software|Freedom of speech|Linux}}\n\n{{Use MDY dates|date=August 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amnesic Incognito}}\n[[Category:Anonymity networks]]\n[[Category:Debian-based distributions]]\n[[Category:Free security software]]\n[[Category:I2P]]\n[[Category:Operating system distributions bootable from read-only media]]\n[[Category:Privacy software]]\n[[Category:Tor (anonymity network)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Tails (Sonic the Hedgehog)}}{{short description|GNU/Linux distribution for anonymity and privacy}}\n{{update|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name = Tails\n| logo = [[File:Tails-logo-flat-inverted.svg|Tails logo|250px]]\n| screenshot = Tails_desktop_3.7.png|Tails OS\n| caption = Tails 3.7 Desktop\n| developer = The Tails project\n| family = [[Unix-like]]\n| source_model = [[Open-source software|Open source]]\n| working_state = Current\n| released = {{Start date and years ago|2009|6|23}}\n| latest_release_version = 4.5\n| latest_release_date = {{Start date and age|2020|04|07}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_4.5|title=Tails 4.5 is out|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| latest_preview_version = 4.0 beta 2\n| latest_preview_date = {{Start date and age|2019|09|04|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/test_4.0-beta2|title=Call for testing: 4.0~beta2|date=2019-09-04|accessdate=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n| marketing target = [[Personal computer]]s\n| kernel_type = [[Monolithic kernel|Monolithic]]\n| userland = [[GNU]]\n| ui = [[GNOME|GNOME 3]]\n| updatemodel = Tails Upgrader<ref>[https://tails.boum.org/contribute/design/incremental_upgrades/ design documentation]</ref>\n| preceded_by = [[Incognito (operating system)|Incognito]]\n| succeeded_by = \n| package_manager = [[dpkg]]\n| supported_platforms = [[x86-64]]<ref>[https://tails.boum.org/doc/about/requirements/ Tails - System requirements]</ref>\n| license = [[GNU General Public License#Version 3|GNU GPLv3]]<ref name=\"h\" />\n| website = {{URL|https://tails.boum.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Tails''' or '''The Amnesic Incognito Live System''' is a [[Security-focused operating system|security-focused]] [[Debian]]-based [[Linux distribution]] aimed at preserving [[privacy]] and [[anonymity]].<ref name=\"lwn\" /> All its incoming and outgoing connections are forced to go through [[Tor (anonymity network)|Tor]],{{r|\"tc\"}} and any and all non-anonymous connections are blocked. The system is designed to be booted as a [[live DVD]] or [[live USB]], and will leave no [[digital footprint]] on the machine unless explicitly told to do so. The [[Tor Project]] has provided financial support for its development.{{r|\"finances\"}}\nAccording to the [[Whonix]] Project, in comparison with other anonymity-focused software or platforms, \"Tails is better suited for high-risk users who face aggressive, targeted surveillance.\"<ref>{{cite web\n| url          = https://www.whonix.org/wiki/Comparison_with_Others#Conclusion\n| title        = Anonymity Operating System Comparison\n| date         = 7 October 2019\n| website      = www.whonix.org\n| access-date  = 7 October 2019\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20190915123511/https://www.whonix.org/wiki/Comparison_with_Others#Conclusion\n| archive-date = 15 September 2019\n| url-status     = live\n}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nTails was first released on 23 June 2009. It is the next iteration of development on [[Incognito (operating system)|Incognito]], a [[Gentoo Linux|Gentoo]]-based Linux distribution.<ref name=\"lj\" /> The Tor Project has provided financial support for its development.<ref name=\"finances\">{{cite web|title=Finances|url=https://tails.boum.org/doc/about/finances/index.en.html|website=Tails|accessdate=13 May 2013|date=4 April 2013}}</ref> Tails has also received funding from the [[Debian Project]], [[Mozilla]], and the [[Freedom of the Press Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/report_2014_05/index.en.html|title=Tails report for May, 2014 |website=Tails|date=14 Jun 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Laura Poitras]], [[Glenn Greenwald]], and [[Barton Gellman]] have each said that Tails was an important tool they used in their work with [[National Security Agency]] whistleblower [[Edward Snowden]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pressfreedomfoundation.org/blog/2014/04/help-support-little-known-privacy-tool-has-been-critical-journalists-reporting-nsa |title=Help Support the Little-Known Privacy Tool That Has Been Critical to Journalists Reporting on the NSA |last=Timm |first=Trevor |date=2 Apr 2014 |website= Freedom of the Press Foundation |accessdate=18 Apr 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2014/04/tails/ |title=Out in the Open: Inside the Operating System Edward Snowden Used to Evade the NSA |last=Finley |first= Klint |date= 14 Apr 2014 |website=WIRED |accessdate=18 Apr 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gizmodo.com/try-the-super-secure-usb-drive-os-that-edward-snowden-i-1563320487 |title=Try the Super-Secure USB Drive OS That Edward Snowden Insists on Using |last=Condliffe |first= Jamie |date= 15 Apr 2014 |website=Gizmodo |accessdate=15 Apr 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAs of release 3.0, Tails requires a [[64-bit processor]] to run.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tails - Tails 3.0 is out|url=https://tails.boum.org/news/version_3.0/index.en.html|website=tails.boum.org|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Bundled software ==\n* [[GNOME]] desktop\n\n=== Networking ===\n* [[Tor (anonymity network)|Tor]] with: Stream isolation, regular, obfs2, obfs3, obfs4, and ScrambleSuit bridges support.\n* [[NetworkManager]] for easy network configuration\n* [[Tor Browser]], a web browser based on [[Firefox|Mozilla Firefox]] and modified to protect anonymity with: \n** Torbutton for anonymity and protection against [[JavaScript]] with all cookies treated as session cookies by default;\n** [[HTTPS Everywhere]] transparently enables [[Transport Layer Security|SSL]]-encrypted connections to a great number of major websites\n** [[NoScript]] to have even more control over JavaScript\n** [[uBlock Origin]] to remove advertisements.\nIt is to note, that due to the fact that Tails include uBlock Origin (compared to the normal Tor Browser Bundle), it could be subject to an attack to determine if the user is using Tails (since the userbase for Tails is less than the Tor Browser Bundle) by checking if the website is blocking advertising.<ref>https://tails.boum.org/doc/about/fingerprint/index.en.html</ref>\n* [[Pidgin (software)|Pidgin]] preconfigured with [[Off-the-Record Messaging|OTR]] for end-to-end encrypted [[instant messaging]]\n* OnionShare for anonymous filesharing\n* [[Mozilla Thunderbird|Thunderbird]] email client with [[Enigmail]] for [[OpenPGP]] support\n* [[Liferea]] [[feed aggregator]]\n* [[Aircrack-ng]] for [[Wi-Fi]] networks [[Information security audit|auditing]]\n* Electrum, an easy-to-use [[bitcoin]] client\n\n===Encryption and privacy software===\n* [[LUKS]] and [[GNOME Disks]] to install and use encrypted storage devices, e.g. for [[USB sticks]]\n* [[GNU Privacy Guard|GnuPG]], the GNU implementation of [[OpenPGP]] for e-mail and data encryption and signing\n* Monkeysign, a tool for OpenPGP key signing and exchange\n* PWGen, a strong [[random password generator]]\n* [[Shamir's Secret Sharing]] using gfshare and ssss\n* GNOME [[virtual keyboard]] as a [[Countermeasure (computer)|countermeasure]] against hardware [[Keystroke logging|keyloggers]]\n* MAT to anonymize [[metadata]] in files\n* [[KeePassXC]] [[password manager]]\n* GtkHash to calculate [[checksum]]s\n* Keyringer, a command line tool to encrypt secrets shared through [[Git (software)|Git]]\n* Paperkey, a command line tool to back up OpenPGP secret keys on paper\n* DeepOnion wallet, an anonymous cryptocurrency using Tor network\n\nUsers can install any other software which is present in Debian GNU/Linux, either through APT (Tails provides three repositories) or [[dpkg]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url          = https://tails.boum.org/contribute/APT_repository/\n| title        = APT repository\n| date         = 7 October 2019\n| website      = tails.boum.org\n| access-date  = 7 October 2019\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20190925050831/https://tails.boum.org/contribute/APT_repository/\n| archive-date = 25 September 2019\n| url-status     = live\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url          = https://tails.boum.org/doc/about/features/index.en.html\n| title        = Features and included software \n| date         = 7 October 2019\n| website      = tails.boum.org\n| access-date  = 7 October 2019\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20190823092502/https://tails.boum.org/doc/about/features/index.en.html\n| archive-date = 23 August 2019\n| url-status     = live\n}}</ref>\n\nOne may choose among a large number of languages and keyboard layouts when the system is [[Booting|booted]].\n\n===Persistency===\n\nTails is by design amnesic. It lives in RAM, and doesn't write to any other drive unless strictly specified. However, it is possible to set up an encrypted persistence volume (for example, within the USB Drive where Tails is installed) to save user data. It is also possible to instruct Tails to automatically install some additional software from the persistence drive, to load bookmarks for the Tor Browser, keep GPG keys or to keep configurations data for other applications. It is important to note, that the encrypted space could be detected by forensic analysis and is not hidden like in the case of [[VeraCrypt]] which offers [[plausible deniability]] and therefore shouldn't be distinguishable from random data.<ref>https://tails.boum.org/doc/first_steps/persistence/configure/index.en.html</ref>\n\n===Security===\n\nDuring the shutdown process, Tails will overwrite most of the used RAM to avoid a [[cold boot attack]].<ref name=\"memory-erasure\">https://tails.boum.org/contribute/design/memory_erasure/</ref>\nAn emergency shutdown can be triggered by physically removing the medium where Tails is installed: a watchdog monitors the status of the boot medium, and if removed then the memory erasing process will begin immediately. This should however only be used in an emergency situation because it could break the file system of the persistence volume, if set up.<ref name=\"memory-erasure\">https://tails.boum.org/contribute/design/memory_erasure/</ref><ref>https://tails.boum.org/doc/first_steps/shutdown/index.en.html</ref>\n\n== Release history ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=3 | {{Version|l|show=110101}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"width:100%; margin-top:0; text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#cfc; padding-top:2em; padding-bottom:2em;\" colspan=\"4\"|Release history\n|-\n! Version<ref name=\"changelog\">{{cite web| url =https://git-tails.immerda.ch/tails/plain/debian/changelog | title=[no title] | author = Tails Developers | date = n.d. | website = Tails | accessdate = 2017-01-05 }}</ref>\n! width=\"140px\"|Release date<ref name=\"changelog\"/>\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n\n|-\n| {{Version | o | 0.1}}\n| {{dts|2009-06-20}}\n|\n* Unreleased, but listed in official changelog\n|-\n| {{Version | o | 0.2}}\n| {{dts|2009-06-23}}\n|\n* First public release.<ref name=\"Murphy-2014-05-01\"/>\n* The project was called Amnesia.<ref name=\"Murphy-2014-05-01\"/><ref name = \"tor-talk mailing list, 2009\" > {{ Cite mailing list | url = https://lists.torproject.org/pipermail/tor-talk/2009-August/002667.html | title = Announce: amnesia Live system (initial release) | date = 2009-08-16 | accessdate = 2019-08-24 | mailing-list = tor-talk mailing list  | df = dmy-all }} </ref>\n|-\n| {{Version | o | 0.3}}\n| {{dts|2009-